net.imglib2.cache.queue

Class BlockingFetchQueues<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.imglib2.cache.queue.BlockingFetchQueues<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - element type.

    public class BlockingFetchQueues<E>
extends Object
    TODO revise javadoc Queueing structure (intended for cache entries to be fetched). There is an array of ArrayDeques, ordered by priority. Elements are put(Object, int, boolean) with a priority and added to one of the queues, accordingly. take() returns an element from the highest priority non-empty queue. Furthermore, there is a prefetch deque of bounded size to provides elements when all the queues are exhausted. clearToPrefetch() empties all queues, and moves the removed elements to the prefetch queue.

    Locking is adapted from ArrayBlockingQueue.

    BlockingFetchQueues is constructed with the number of priority levels n. Priorities are consecutive integers 0 ... n-1, where 0 is the highest priority. Priorities of enqueued entries are clamped to the range 0 ... n-1.

    Author:
    Tobias Pietzsch

      • put

        public void put(E element,
                int priority,
                boolean enqueuToFront)
        Add element to the queue of the specified priority. The element can be added to the front or back of the queue.
        Parameters:
        element - the element to enqueue
        priority - lower values mean higher priority
        enqueuToFront - if true, enqueue element at the front (LIFO). if false, enqueue element at the back (FIFO)

      • put_unsafe

        public void put_unsafe(E element,
                       int priority,
                       boolean enqueuToFront)
        Equivalent to put(Object, int, boolean), but priorities are not clamped to the allowed range. Will throw an ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException if priority < 0 or priority >= numPriorities.

        Add element to the queue of the specified priority. The element can be added to the front or back of the queue.

        Parameters:
        element - the element to enqueue
        priority - lower values mean higher priority
        enqueuToFront - if true, enqueue element at the front (LIFO). if false, enqueue element at the back (FIFO)

      • take

        public E take()
       throws InterruptedException
        Remove and return an element from the highest priority non-empty queue. If all queues are empty, then return an element from the prefetch deque. If the prefetch deque is also empty, then block.
        Returns:
        element.
        Throws:
        InterruptedException

      • pause

        public void pause()
           throws InterruptedException
        Pause the queue. While the queue is paused, all consumer threads are held in take(). The pause() method itself blocks until all (of the pre-defined number of) consumer threads have arrived in take().

        While the queue is paused, all calls to take() block. (Calls to put() are not affected.)

        Throws:
        InterruptedException

      • clearToPrefetch

        public void clearToPrefetch()
        Atomically removes all of the elements from this queue. All queues will be empty after this call returns. Removed elements are moved to the prefetch deque.
